{{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=United States v. Comstock |ArgueDate=January 12 |ArgueYear=2010 |DecideDate=May 17 |DecideYear=2010 |FullName=United States, Petitioner v. Graydon Earl Comstock, Jr., et al. |USVol=560 |USPage=126 |ParallelCitations=130 S. Ct. 1949; 176 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 878 |Docket=08-1224 |Prior=507 [[F. Supp. 2d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/20071029507fsupp2d5221993 522] ([[E.D.N.C.]] 2007); affirmed, 551 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20090108064 274] ([[4th Cir.]] 2009); [[Certiorari|cert]]. granted, {{ussc|557|918|2009|el=no}}. |Subsequent=On remand, 627 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20101206064 513] (4th Cir. 2010). |Holding=The federal government may order the civil commitment of a mentally ill, sexually dangerous person beyond the conclusion of his federal sentence. |SCOTUS=2009-2010 |Majority=Breyer |JoinMajority=Roberts, Stevens, Ginsburg, Sotomayor |Concurrence=Kennedy |Concurrence2=Alito |Dissent=Thomas |JoinDissent=Scalia (except part III–A–1–b) |LawsApplied= }}
'''''United States v. Comstock''''', 560 U.S. 126 (2010), was a decision by the [[Supreme Court of the United States]], which held that the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]] has authority under the [[Necessary and Proper Clause]] to require the [[involuntary commitment|civil commitment]] of individuals already in Federal custody.<ref>JESSE J. HOLLAND, [http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory?id=10666088 Court: Sexually dangerous can be kept in prison], [[Associated Press]]. Retrieved 5-16-2010.</ref> The practice, introduced by the [[Adam Walsh Child Protection and Safety Act]], was upheld against a challenge that it fell outside the [[enumerated powers]] granted to [[United States Congress|Congress]] by the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]]. The decision did not rule on any other aspect of the law's constitutionality, because only the particular issue of Congressional authority was properly before the Court.<ref name="scotuspdf">{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/09pdf/08-1224.pdf |title=08-1224 United States v. Comstock (05/17/2010) |format=PDF |publisher=Supremecourt.gov |accessdate=2010-06-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703652104574652392015371328?mod=WSJ_Opinion_AboveLEFTTop |title=Predators and the Constitution |publisher=WSJ.com |date=2010-01-19 |accessdate=2010-06-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jan/18/opinion/la-ed-sex18-2010jan18 |title=Sex offenders behind bars: How long? |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=2010-01-18 |accessdate=2010-06-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2010/01/17/US-Supreme-Court-Throwing-away-the-key-for-sex-offenders/UPI-43591263717000/ |title=U.S. Supreme Court: Throwing away the key for sex offenders? |publisher=UPI.com |date= |first=Michael |last=Kirkland |accessdate=2010-06-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first=Bill |last=Mears |url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/CRIME/05/17/scotus.sex.offenders/ |title=Supreme Court: Sex offenders can be held indefinitely |publisher=CNN |date=2010-05-17 |accessdate=2010-06-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-05-17/sex-offender-commitment-law-upheld-by-u-s-high-court-update1-.html |title=Sex-Offender Commitment Law Upheld by U.S. High Court |publisher=BusinessWeek |date=2010-05-17 |first=Greg |last=Stohr |accessdate=2010-06-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Biskupic |first=Joan |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/judicial/2010-05-17-sexually-dangerous_N.htm |title=Sex offenders may be confined past sentences |publisher=Usa Today |date=2010-05-18 |accessdate=2010-06-12}}</ref>
== Background == Six days before Graydon Earl Comstock was to have completed a 37-month sentence for receiving [[child pornography]], Attorney General [[Alberto R. Gonzales]] certified that Comstock was a [[sexually dangerous person]]. The law that Attorney General Gonzales was applying was ruled unconstitutional by lower courts on the grounds it exceeded Congress’s constitutional authority. Argued in January 2010 by [[Solicitor General of the United States|Solicitor General]] [[Elena Kagan]], the position of the United States was that the [[Necessary and Proper Clause]] gave Congress the power to enact the law.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/18/us/politics/18offenders.html Justices Rule That Sex Offenders May Be Held After Their Sentences End], nytimes.com, by Adam Liptak, May 17, 2010</ref>
== Decision == [[Stephen Breyer]] delivered the opinion of the Court, which decided that the "Necessary and Proper" Clause permitted Congress to enact such a provision. John Roberts, John Paul Stevens, Ruth Bader Ginsburg, and Sonia Sotomayor joined Breyer's opinion. Anthony Kennedy and Samuel Alito filed opinions concurring in the judgment. Clarence Thomas filed a dissenting opinion in which Antonin Scalia joined in all but Part III– A–1–b.<ref name="scotuspdf"/>
=== Five considerations === The Court said: "We base this conclusion on five considerations, taken together." The five considerations are as follows. * First, the Necessary and Proper Clause grants Congress broad power to enact laws that are "rationally related" and "reasonably adapted" to executing the other enumerated powers. * Second, the statute at issue "constitutes a modest addition" to related statutes that have existed for many decades. * Third, the statute in question reasonably extends longstanding policy. * Fourth, the statute properly accounts for state interests, by ending the federal government's role "with respect to an individual covered by the statute" whenever a state requests. * Fifth, the statute is narrowly tailored to only address the legitimate federal interest.
